  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "internal team communications",
  "user_goals_summary": "This user writes internal messages that must land operationally \u2014 every section should do a clear job. They prioritize reader-centered framing (acknowledging the audience's reality before justifying decisions), lean information density (milestones over process descriptions), and closings that leave the reader with a concrete picture of what happens next rather than sentiment.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user thinks about emails structurally \u2014 each section has a job, and they'll iterate until it does that job cleanly. They will consistently trade warmth for clarity; never pad a closing with gratitude when it could end on an action. When they say something 'isn't working,' it's almost always about the *function* of a section (what it accomplishes for the reader) rather than word-level style issues. Present options when the fix is small and tonal; present a single revised section when the fix is structural."
}

RECENT CONVERSATION CONTEXT (shows the user's writing preferences and interactions):
ll — just one sentence before the news that gives the reader half a step of footing before the floor shifts. A few options for that opening line:

Option 1: "Before we get to launch preparations, there's something important the whole team needs to know."

Option 2: "Testing turned up something this week that changes our launch plans."

Option 3: "I want to make sure everyone hears this from me directly, and not through the grapevine."

Option 2 is probably the strongest — it signals that something has changed without being dramatic about it, and it flows naturally into "We found a critical bug in testing" without feeling like a preamble for its own sake. But Option 3 might be right if the bug has already started circulating informally and you want to get ahead of that.

Which direction feels right, and I'll drop it into the full draft?

[Message #17 — user]
Option 2 works. Go ahead and put the full email together with that opener.

